Next week, the Social Committee of the Riigikogu will again discuss the law on providing psychiatric help.
Psychiatrists are the only specialist doctors to whom a child under the age of eighteen needs parental permission.
Specialists involved in the commission's work have repeatedly pointed out the need to change the law.
Ave H suddenly asked why the amendment has been stuck in the Riigikogu.
A loophole in the law does not allow young people under the age of eighteen to seek psychiatric help without their parents' permission.
Although the government has repeatedly confirmed the need to change the law, young people continue to go without help every month.
