The topic has been discussed six times in the social committee of the Riigikogu. Various aspects of the problem have been explained by specialists, representatives of thirty-six organizations, they also signed a joint appeal, which justifies the importance of the amendment to the law.
It has been a year and a half since the chancellor of justice drew the country's attention to the fact that this small change in the law would be fair and necessary for young people.
Today we are in a situation where the social committee of the Riigikogu has been processing this issue for almost a year, including the Ministry of Education, Ministry of Justice, Ministry of Social Affairs, including the Prime Minister and the Minister of Social Affairs, have expressed their support for this small change in the law. And we still process and cannot process him.
What at first seemed like a small and simple change in the law has grown into a fundamental confrontation. EKRE member Urmas Espenberg, who is part of the social committee, says that in theory they agree that young people could, in exceptional cases, have access to a psychiatrist's talk without a parent's permission. In practice, no agreement is reached. According to Espenberg, the two exceptional cases in which a young person could turn to a psychiatrist without a parent are the absence of a guardian or domestic violence.
I certainly don't agree with the fact that everyone starts going to psychiatrists of their own accord, so that any child should go to the counseling of a psychologist first, and then the psychologist will see if, if, what to do next.
So what are the opponents of the law changes afraid of? Do you not trust young people or do you not trust specialists, i.e. psychiatrists?
Espenberg cites the need to cooperate with the family as the main reasons, the fear that too strong drugs will be prescribed to young people, as well as the fear that mental problems will become a fashionable disease or that young people will start selling the prescribed drugs on the black market.
After all, young people are prone to trying all kinds of things, and when the word gets out that everyone can go now, then the story of antidepressants will be left open, then maybe they will start selling it to each other.
The psychiatrist refutes the fears of the opponents of the law changes, the doctor's task and competence is to assess the patient's condition and act accordingly.
It is always the doctor's wisdom to see through these situations, to see what motives actually come and how this drug use is, that is, that there are rules for this, by following which we can prevent most of these problems.
According to doctors and youth workers, the problem is serious and requires action.
I turned to thirteen youth workers from four different institutions working with young people, and a third of them have actually had contact with the question where a child needs psychiatric help, but due to the parent's answer, it has not been found.
I also asked them about their stories, sometimes the stories are scary to say the least, two of these stories led to suicide attempts, luckily unsuccessful attempts, one of them is an ongoing process where the child then does not dare to contact his parents, as his parents are very strongly convinced that mental health issues is something that is only a question for the insane or strongly clerical.
Urmas Espemberg proposes a solution that another adult in contact with young people could issue a referral or permission to a psychiatrist.
In practice, it looks like we have all kinds of networks, it's the youth and child protection network, then there's the same police where certain cases are registered, they can immediately make a referral there, then there are school psychologists, who you can turn to, these possibilities there are many, and there are many psychologists in Estonia, and they are all relatively unpractised, so that then you should think about solving these things somehow, rather than blaming each other.
However, each stage of the gap increases the bureaucracy and requires additional forces, at the moment it is a problem to meet the existing requirements, only thirty-nine percent of Estonian schools have a psychologist at work, which means that more than half of the schools have to do without a psychologist.
Where they are, they are very good, and where they are not, they are sorely lacking.
